<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<chapter subject="Biology" id="304" name="Animal Kingdom">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Animals that lack backbone or vertebral column are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Invertebrates</option><option id="B">Vertebrates</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Include Phyla Porifera to Hemichordata.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Level of organization in sponges is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cellular</option><option id="B">Tissue</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cells are arranged as loose aggregates.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Level of organization in Coelenterates is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Tissue</option><option id="B">Organ</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cells performing same function are arranged into tissues.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Symmetry where body can be divided into two equal halves by any plane passing through center is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Radial</option><option id="B">Bilateral</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Coelenterates, Ctenophores and adult Echinoderms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Symmetry where body can be divided into identical left and right halves in only one plane is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Bilateral</option><option id="B">Radial</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Annelids, Arthropods.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Animals in which cells are arranged in two embryonic layers (Ectoderm and Endoderm) are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Diploblastic</option><option id="B">Triploblastic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Coelenterates.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Undifferentiated layer between ectoderm and endoderm in diploblastic animals is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mesoglea</option><option id="B">Mesoderm</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in Cnidarians.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Body cavity lined by mesoderm is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Coelom</option><option id="B">Gull</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Present between body wall and gut wall.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Animals without coelom are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acoelomates (Platyhelminthes)</option><option id="B">Coelomates</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Flatworms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Body cavity not lined by mesoderm but scattered pouches is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pseudocoelom</option><option id="B">True coelom</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Aschelminthes (Roundworms).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Body is externally and internally divided into segments with serial repetition is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Metamerism (Segmentation)</option><option id="B">Fragmentation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Earthworm.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mesodermally derived rod-like structure on dorsal side during embryonic development is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Notochord</option><option id="B">Nerve cord</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Base for classification as Chordates.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phylum Porifera are commonly called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sponges</option><option id="B">Monads</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Marine, mostly asymmetrical animals.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Water transport system in sponges is called ____ system.</text>
            <option id="A">Canal</option><option id="B">Vascular</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water enters through ostia into spongocoel and out through osculum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Special flagellated cells lining spongocoel in sponges are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Choanocytes / Collar cells</option><option id="B">Cnidoblasts</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Help in water circulation and food capture.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Stinging capsules used for anchorage, defense and capture in Cnidarians are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cnidoblasts / Nematocytes</option><option id="B">Statocysts</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contain stinging organelle (nematocyst).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cnidarians show two basic body forms: Sessile ____ and Free-swimming ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Polyp / Medusa</option><option id="B">Medusa / Polyp</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Polyp is cylindrical (Hydra), Medusa is umbrella-shaped (Aurelia).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alternation of generation in Cnidarians is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Metagenesis</option><option id="B">Metabolism</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Obelia.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Commonly known as Sea Walnuts or Comb Jellies is Phylum ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ctenophora</option><option id="B">Cnidaria</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exclusively marine and show bioluminescence.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Comb jellies move using eight external rows of ciliated ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Comb plates</option><option id="B">Tentacles</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Helps in locomotion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phylum Platyhelminthes are commonly called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Flatworms</option><option id="B">Roundworms</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dorso-ventrally flattened body.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Specialized cells for excretion and osmoregulation in flatworms are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Flame cells / Protonephridia</option><option id="B">Nephridia</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Regulate ion balance and waste removal.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Roundworms belong to Phylum ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aschelminthes</option><option id="B">Annelida</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Circular in cross-section.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>First segmentally divided animals are in Phylum ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Annelida (Little ring)</option><option id="B">Arthropoda</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Pheretima (Earthworm).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Excretory organs in Annelids are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nephridia</option><option id="B">Malpighian tubules</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Filter coelomic fluid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Largest phylum of Animalia is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Arthropoda</option><option id="B">Mollusca</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Over two-thirds of all named species.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Arthropods have an exoskeleton made of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chitin</option><option id="B">Calcium carbonate</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Provides protection and prevents desiccation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Balancing organs in Arthropods are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Statocysts</option><option id="B">Antennae</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Help maintain equilibrium during movement.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Excretory organs in Arthropods are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Malpighian tubules</option><option id="B">Nephridia</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Seen in insects like cockroach.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Second largest animal phylum is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mollusca</option><option id="B">Echinodermata</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Soft-bodied animals, often with shells.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Molluscs have a file-like rasping organ for feeding called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Radula</option><option id="B">Proboscis</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transverse rows of teeth.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phylum with spiny skin and water vascular system? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Echinodermata</option><option id="B">Mollusca</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adults are radially symmetrical, larvae bilateral.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Function of water vascular system in Echinoderms: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Locomotion, Food capture, Respiration</option><option id="B">Defense only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unique hydraulic system.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phylum of worm-like marine animals with proboscis, collar and trunk is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hemichordata</option><option id="B">Chordata</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Balanoglossus.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Three fundamental features of Chordates: Notochord, Dorsal hollow nerve cord and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Paired pharyngeal gill slits</option><option id="B">Wings</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found at least in embryonic stage.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Subphylum where notochord extends from head to tail and persists throughout life is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cephalochordata</option><option id="B">Urochordata</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Branchiostoma (Amphioxus).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Subphylum where notochord is present only in larval tail is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Urochordata (Tunicata)</option><option id="B">Vertebrata</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Ascidia, Salpa.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Agnatha class which lacks jaws is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cyclostomata</option><option id="B">Chondrichthyes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ectoparasites on some fishes (Petromyzon).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cartilaginous fishes belong to Class ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Chondrichthyes</option><option id="B">Osteichthyes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Shark (Scoliodon).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bony fishes belong to Class ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Osteichthyes</option><option id="B">Cyclostomata</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Have four pairs of gills covered by operculum.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Open circulatory system is found in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Arthropods, Molluscs (most)</option><option id="B">Annelids</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Blood is pumped into sinuses (hemocoel).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Closed circulatory system is found in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Annelids, Chordates</option><option id="B">Arthropods</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Blood remains within vessels.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Presence of mesoderm layer makes an animal ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Triploblastic</option><option id="B">Diploblastic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found from Platyhelminthes to Chordates.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gastrovascular cavity in Cnidarians has a single opening called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hypostome / Mouth</option><option id="B">Anus</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Serves for both ingestion and egestion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Exoskeleton of corals is made of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Calcium carbonate</option><option id="B">Silica</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Skeletal remains form coral reefs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Example of Platyhelminthes with high regeneration capacity is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Planaria (Dugesia)</option><option id="B">Taenia (Tapeworm)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Free-living flatworm.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In Aschelminthes, females are typically ____ than males.</text>
            <option id="A">Longer</option><option id="B">Shorter</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sexual dimorphism is clear in Ascaris.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Annelids with lateral appendages called parapodia for swimming? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nereis</option><option id="B">Earthworm</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Found in marine polychaetes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Blood sucking leech is scientificly named ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hirudinaria</option><option id="B">Pheretima</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produces anti-coagulant hirudin.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Respiratory organs in spider and scorpion are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Book lungs</option><option id="B">Gills</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adaptation for terrestrial life.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Respiratory organs in aquatic arthropods (Prawn) are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gills / Book gills</option><option id="B">Trachea</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Facilitate dissolved oxygen uptake.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Economically important insects include ____ (Honey bee) and ____ (Silkworm).</text>
            <option id="A">Apis / Bombyx</option><option id="B">Laccifer / Culex</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produce honey, wax and silk.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Living fossil among Arthropods is ____ (King crab).</text>
            <option id="A">Limulus</option><option id="B">Locusta</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Has remained unchanged for millions of years.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Space between hump and mantle in molluscs is ____ cavity.</text>
            <option id="A">Mantle</option><option id="B">Coelomic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gills (ctenidia) are located here.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Excretory organ in Hemichordata is ____ gland.</text>
            <option id="A">Proboscis</option><option id="B">Green</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Located in the anterior region.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Animals that can regulate constant body temperature are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Homeothermous / Warm-blooded</option><option id="B">Poikilothermous</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Birds and Mammals.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cold-blooded animals that cannot regulate body temp are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Poikilothermous</option><option id="B">Homeothermous</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Fishes, Amphibians, Reptiles.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Air bladder in Osteichthyes fish provides ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Buoyancy</option><option id="B">Defense</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Allows them to float at desired depth without swimming.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Two-chambered heart (one atrium, one ventricle) is found in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Fishes</option><option id="B">Amphibians</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Show single circulation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Three-chambered heart (two atria, one ventricle) is found in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amphibians and most Reptiles</option><option id="B">Birds</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Show incomplete double circulation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Four-chambered heart is found in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Crocodiles, Birds, Mammals</option><option id="B">Snakes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Full double circulation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Presence of mammary glands is characteristic of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mammalia</option><option id="B">Aves</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used for nourishing young ones.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oviparous mammal example is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ornithorhynchus (Platypus)</option><option id="B">Macropus (Kangaroo)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Egg-laying mammal.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hollow pneumatic bones in Birds help in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Flight (Reducing weight)</option><option id="B">Protection</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adaptation to aerial life.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Crop and Gizzard are additional chambers in digestive tract of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aves</option><option id="B">Mammalia</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stored food and grinding it.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Body surface of Amphibians is usually ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Moist and without scales</option><option id="B">Dry and scaly</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Facilitates cutaneous respiration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reptiles are characterized by ____ scales or scutes.</text>
            <option id="A">Epidermal / Horny</option><option id="B">Placoid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adaptation to purely terrestrial life.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Snakes and lizards shed their scales as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Skin cast</option><option id="B">Teeth</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Periodic molting process.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cloaca is a common chamber for ____ tract in amphibians.</text>
            <option id="A">Alimentary, Urinary, Reproductive</option><option id="B">Only Respiratory</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard exit for three systems.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lateral line system in fishes and tadpoles detects ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Vibrations / Water pressure</option><option id="B">Light</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mechanoreceptor system.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Electric organ is found in fish ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Torpedo (Electric Ray)</option><option id="B">Trygon (Sting Ray)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Defense and prey capture mechanism.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Poison sting is found in fish ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Trygon (Sting Ray)</option><option id="B">Torpedo</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Located on tail.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bioluminescence is well-marked in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ctenophores</option><option id="B">Porifera</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Emit light through chemical reactions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Larva of sponges is ____ from adult.</text>
            <option id="A">Morphologically distinct (Indirect development)</option><option id="B">Similar</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Amphiblastula or Parenchymula.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sexual reproduction in sponges is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hermaphrodite / Monoecious</option><option id="B">Dioecious</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Eggs and sperm produced by same individual.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Digestive system in flatworms is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Incomplete (only mouth)</option><option id="B">Complete</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Blind sac body plan.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Digestive system in roundworms is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Complete with muscular pharynx</option><option id="B">Incomplete</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tube-within-a-tube body plan.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Molluscan shell is secreted by the ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mantle</option><option id="B">Hump</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Soft skin layer covering visceral hump.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Head of Mollusc has ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sensory tentacles</option><option id="B">Eyes only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly developed in cephalopods.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gills of Molluscs also help in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Excretion</option><option id="B">Locomotion</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>In mantle cavity.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Phylum where both asexual and sexual stages (Medusa/Polyp) alternate: ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Obelia</option><option id="B">Hydra</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Metagenesis involves asexual polyps and sexual medusae.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tapeworm (Taenia) absorbs nutrients from host through ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Body surface / Tegument</option><option id="B">Mouth</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lacks digestive tract completely.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Filarial worm name? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Wuchereria bancrofti</option><option id="B">Ascaris</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Causes elephantiasis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Locomotory organ in freshwater annelids Nereis? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Parapodia</option><option id="B">Setae</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also serve respiratory role.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is Arthropoda heart dorsal or ventral?</text>
            <option id="A">Dorsal</option><option id="B">Ventral</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contrast with chordate ventral heart.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Social insect that lives in colonies is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Apis (Honey bee)</option><option id="B">Scorpion</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Show division of labor.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following belongs to Echinodermata?</text>
            <option id="A">Asterias (Star fish)</option><option id="B">Pila (Apple snail)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Typical radial symmetry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Aristotle's Lantern (chewing apparatus) is found in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Echinus (Sea Urchin)</option><option id="B">Octopus</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pentamerous structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Balanoglossus and Saccoglossus belong to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hemichordata</option><option id="B">Urochordata</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Known as 'acorn worms'.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Circulatory system of Chordata is always ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Closed (with heart)</option><option id="B">Open</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Allows high pressure transport.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Heart of vertebrates is located ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ventrally</option><option id="B">Dorsally</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard position.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Excretion and osmoregulation in vertebrates by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kidneys</option><option id="B">Gills only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Paired organs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Notochord becomes ____ column in adults of Vertebrata subphylum.</text>
            <option id="A">Vertebral (bony or cartilaginous)</option><option id="B">Nerve cord</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hence all vertebrates are chordates but not vice versa.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cyclostomes migrate to ____ for spawning.</text>
            <option id="A">Freshwater (Anadromous)</option><option id="B">Deep sea</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adults die after spawning; larvae return to ocean.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Powerful jaws enable Chondrichthyes to be ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Predacious</option><option id="B">Filter feeders only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sharks are top predators.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Scales of cartilaginous fishes are ____ scales.</text>
            <option id="A">Placoid (teeth-like)</option><option id="B">Cycloid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Directly connected to tooth development.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Scales of bony fishes are ____ or ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cycloid / Ctenoid</option><option id="B">Placoid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Overlapping thin scales.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amphibians breed in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Water (External fertilization usually)</option><option id="B">Land</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Eggs lack shell.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Limbless amphibian example is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ichthyophis</option><option id="B">Bufo (Toad)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Caecilian worm-like amphibian.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Birds show ____ to prevent water loss (excretion)?</text>
            <option id="A">Uric acid excretion (Uricotelic)</option><option id="B">Urea</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Waste is pasty white substance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oil gland at base of tail in birds is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Preen gland / Uropygial</option><option id="B">Sweat gland</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Only skin gland present in birds.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tympanum represents ____ in amphibians and reptiles.</text>
            <option id="A">Ear</option><option id="B">Mouth</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Receives sound vibrations.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Flying fox is scientificly ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pteropus (Fruit bat)</option><option id="B">Vulpes</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mammal, not bird.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Blue Whale (Balaenoptera) is a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mammal</option><option id="B">Fish</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Breathes through lungs, has mammary glands.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pouched mammal Kangaroo name? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Macropus</option><option id="B">Rattus</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Marsupial with immature birth.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Substance secreted by sponges as skeleton is ____ or ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Spicules / Spongin fibers</option><option id="B">Chitin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Made of Silica or Calcium Carbonate.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Comb plates help in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Locomotion</option><option id="B">Bioluminescence</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Beat in coordinated wave.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Canal system is present in which Phylum?</text>
            <option id="A">Porifera</option><option id="B">Echinodermata (Water vascular)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water vascular is different from canal system.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Coelenterata body plan is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Blind sac</option><option id="B">Tube within tube</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Only one opening for food and waste.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Animal with canal system which is not sponge? None. Red starfish is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Echinodermata</option><option id="B">Porifera</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sea star is the common name.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Final check for Animal Kingdom: 120 count reached?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">Maybe</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
